  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "As no established survey instruments with practice-proven suitability for the present research question exist, we developed novel scales closely aligned with best practices in this field.",
    "That is, we decided on a relatively low number of response options with individual, unambiguous labels and used symmetrical scales with non-overlapping categories (23, 24).",
    "The final seven-point Likert scales went from \"Extremely unreliable\" to \"Extremely reliable\", from \"Extremely difficult to understand\" to \"Extremely easy to understand\" and from \"Extremely unempathic\" to \"Extremely empathic\", respectively.",
    "For the \"AI\"-label group, ratings for each scale were positively correlated with participants' attitudes toward AI (perceived opportunities compared to risks, perceived impact for healthcare), ps ≤.022, thus pointing to high conceptual validity of our scales.",
    "We employed a unifactorial between-subjects design, with the manipulated factor being the supposed author of the presented medical information (Human, AI, Human + AI; see Figure S5 in the supplementary information)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
